latestPosts.caption:
As a makeup artist, I see things that most clients don’t and that’s what helps me enhance your natural beauty in the best way possible. 💄✨

Here’s what I notice (that you probably don’t): 👇

👀 1. Your Skin Texture & Type:
Before I even touch a product, I assess your skin. Is it dry, oily, or combo? Is there texture, dehydration, or sensitivity? This helps me choose the right prep and products for a flawless, lasting base.

🎨 2. Your Undertone:
Many clients bring a foundation that looks perfect until I see it clashing under different lighting. I match your undertone, not just your surface shade, so it blends seamlessly into your neck and chest.

👁️ 3. Eye Shape & Space:
I look at your lid space, crease, and eye symmetry to decide whether to go for a smokey eye, soft cut crease, or lifted liner. Every eye tells a different story!

🔍 4. Flashback-Triggering Products:
I avoid powders, SPFs, or concealers that cause flashback in photos because you deserve to glow in every light!

latestPosts.caption:
When I first started doing makeup, I made mistakes that most beginners do and that’s okay! 

Every flaw was a lesson, and every lesson made me better. 

Here’s what I wish I knew earlier 👇

💄 1. Skipping Skin Prep:
I used to jump straight into foundation without moisturizing or priming resulting in patchy, uneven texture that never lasted long.

💄 2. Using the Wrong Shade:
Matching foundation to my wrist or hand? Guilty! Undertones matter more than you think.

💄 3. Overdoing Brows & Contour:
Back then, bold was trendy—but now I know how important balance and blending is for a natural, structured look.

💄 4. Ignoring Face Shapes & Features:
One look doesn’t fit all. Now, I customize every look based on my client’s features, not trends.

💄 5. Not Cleaning Brushes Regularly:
A clean brush = flawless blending (and healthy skin). Lesson learned the hard way.

We all grow, we all learn. If you’re starting out don’t be too hard on yourself. Practice, refine, and evolve 🌸

As a professional makeup artist, hygiene isn’t optional it’s non-negotiable. 

Clean tools, sanitized products, and safe practices protect both you and your skin.

Here’s a glimpse into my hygiene protocol:

✔ Brushes are deep-cleaned and sanitized between every client

✔ Sponges are either disposable or thoroughly washed after each use

✔ Lipsticks, liners, and pencils are sharpened or wiped with alcohol before use

✔ Products are never double-dipped palettes and spatulas are used for application

✔ I sanitize my hands frequently and use hand sanitizers before touching your face

✔ Tools like lash curlers, tweezers, and scissors are disinfected before each session

Whether it’s a bridal booking or a party glam, my priority is your safety and comfort. Makeup should never come at the cost of hygiene. 
Ask questions, be aware, and never settle for anything less than clean and professional service.

latestPosts.caption:
Whether you’re a beginner or even someone who’s been doing makeup for years, eye makeup can be tricky. 

One small error can change the whole look—either making your eyes appear smaller, uneven, or just not as defined. But don’t worry! 

Let’s go over some easy do’s and don’ts that will instantly level up your eye game:

✅ DO blend your eyeshadow well, harsh lines make the eyes look unpolished.

❌ DON’T skip primer, it helps your eyeshadow last longer and prevents creasing.

✅ DO curl your lashes before applying mascara for that wide-eyed effect.

❌ DON’T overload mascara on the lower lashes, it can drag your eyes down.

✅ DO apply eyeliner according to your eye shape to enhance naturally.

❌ DON’T use too dark shades on the crease without blending, it can make the eyes look sunken.

✅ DO highlight your inner corners and brow bone for a lifted look.

❌ DON’T forget to clean up fallout, it instantly freshens the eye area.

Mastering these small yet impactful steps will transform your eye makeup from basic to professional. ✨💫

Which of these mistakes have you been making? Let me know in the comments! 👇

Ever wondered why your makeup looks perfect in the mirror but suddenly patchy or washed out in photos? 

It’s not your makeup — it’s the lighting!

Here’s how different lighting affects your makeup:

🌤 Natural Light: The most honest! It reveals true colors, textures, and flaws. Great for checking foundation match and blending.

💡 Studio Light: Softboxes & ring lights diffuse light evenly, making skin look smooth and radiant. Ideal for creating content or tutorials — but might not reflect how makeup looks in real life.

🔆 Event Lighting (Halogens/LEDs): These lights can be warm or cool toned and often unpredictable. Warm lights may make your makeup look more orange or yellow; cool lights can wash you out.

📸 Flash Photography: Flash reflects off dewy/highlighter-heavy areas and can make your base look oily or white if not set properly (hello, flashback!).

Pro Tip:
As a makeup artist, I always test the final look under multiple light sources — mirror, natural light, and camera flash — so your glam stays flawless everywhere.

✨Remember: Lighting changes how we perceive makeup — not its actual quality. Trust your artist, trust the technique!

Makeup Pro Tip Part - 8

Got a pimple? Don’t stress—blend smart! Instead of dragging your foundation over it, gently dab using light pressure. 

This technique avoids disturbing the texture and helps prevent that dreaded patchy look. Use a damp beauty sponge or a small brush and press the product in place for a flawless, natural finish. 

The goal is to cover, not cake. Remember, skin has texture and that’s totally normal—enhance your beauty, don’t hide it! 💖
